ed layout: Urban laws in Scotland through manuscript and print -- t11 Visual pragmatics of an early modern book: Printers’ paratextual choices in the editions of The School of Vertue -- t12 Paratextual presentation of Christopher St German’s Doctor and Student 1528–1886 -- t13 Reflections on visuality and textual reception -- tSection 4: New to Old -- tIntroduction to new to old -- t14 Information design and information structure in the Middle English prose Brut -- t15 Disruptive practice: Multimodality, innovation and standardisation from the medieval to the digital text -- t16 “It makes it more real”: A comparative analysis of Twitter use in live blogs and quotations in older news media from a reader response perspective -- t17 New methods, old data: Using digital technologies to explore nineteenth century letter writing practices -- t18 Transhistoricizing multimodality: Reflections on the how-to -- tPostscript: You say you want a revolution? Histories and futures of researching the digital, a view from the south -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aStudies of digital communication technologies often focus on the apparently unique set of multimodal resources afforded to users and the development of innovative linguistic strategies for performing mediatised identities and maintaining online social networks.This edited volume interrogates the novelty of such practices by establishing a transhistorical approach to the study of digital communication. The transhistorical approach explores language practices as lived experiences grounded in historical contexts, and aims to identify those elements of human behaviour that transcend historical boundaries, looking beyond specific developments in communication technologies to understand the enduring motivations and social concerns that drive human communication.The volume reveals long-term patterns in the indexical functions of seemingly innovative written and multimodal resources and the ideologies that underpin them, and shows that methods are not necessarily contingent on their datasets: historical analytic frameworks can be applied to digital data and newer approaches used to understand historical data. These insights present exciting opportunities for English language researchers, both historical and modern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021)1 aAdami, Elisabetta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarton, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaridge, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuly, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeumert, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDriel, Martine van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Mel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Mel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFitzmaurice, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiaxoglou, Korina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Rodney H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKopaczyk, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKádár, Dániel Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiira, Aino, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyons, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Colette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 